# CAV 2026 Artifact

Paper title: A mechanised, bidirectional type system for bit-width determination in SystemVerilog

Claimed badges: Available + Functional + Reusable

Justification for the badges:

- Functional:
  The artifact is self-contained and reproduces the core technical claims of
  the paper by checking all Rocq developments and the extracted algorithm.
  The full proof scripts are included.
  It replicates:
  - Core formal development compiles: Smoke test point (1), Full review point (1)
  - Equivalence proof between rule system and specification (Theorem 2): Smoke test point (2), Full review point (2)
  - Algorithm correctness theorem (Theorem 3): Smoke test point (3), Full review point (3)
  - Verified extraction of the typing algorithm to OCaml: Smoke test point (4), Full review point (4)
  - Documentation generation over the proved development: Smoke test point (5), Full review point (5)

- Reusable:
  The artifact is reusable beyond the paper evaluation.
  - License and reuse rights:
    The artifact is distributed under the MIT license,
    which allows reuse, repurposing, modification, and redistribution.
  - Dependencies and maintenance:
    Dependencies are documented, proof checking relies on standard Rocq tooling.
  - Reuse beyond paper claims:
    The development is modular and can be reused to extend the language,
    add rules, or adapt extraction.
  - Interfaces and extensibility:
    The source is open and a generated documentation is generated with the
    artifact.
  - Portability:
    The artifact can be used in different environments: either inside Docker or
    natively with opam on Linux-compatible systems.
    The source code is included in the sources.zip archive for easy browsing and
    modifications.

Requirements:

- RAM: 8 GB recommended (4 GB minimum)
- CPU cores: 2+ recommended (1 minimum)
- Time (smoke test): 10 minutes
- Time (full review): 10 minutes

external connectivity: NO

---

## ** SMOKE TEST **

The smoke test checks that the project builds and that key claims can be
validated quickly.

Run the following to load the Docker image:

    docker load < docker-image.tar.zstd

After that, create a output directory writable to other then run the docker image:

    mkdir -p "`pwd`/output"
    chmod o+rw "`pwd`/output"
    docker run -v "`pwd`/output:/workspace/doc" --rm -it docker-verilog

> Ensure that the "`pwd`/output" directory is writable for "other".

> Note for Fedora/RHEL/CentOS users:
> If you have SELinux enforcing, you may encounter a "Permission denied" error during
> step 5 (make doc). To fix this, append :Z to your volume mount in the run command:
> docker run -v "`pwd``/output:/workspace/doc:Z" --rm -it docker-verilog

The command above starts the docker container and places you in a bash
environment, where you can inspect the source code or run the experiments. `-v`
option will mount `output` folder in your current directory to the
corresponding folder within the container where the generated documentation will be
stored. This will allow you to view the documentation even after the
container has stopped running. `--rm` is an optional flag that creates a
disposable container that will be deleted upon exit.

## Smoke-test commands

From the repository root:

    make build

Expected runtime: usually under 10 minutes on a standard laptop.
Expected result: build ends with "Build complete." and no proof errors.

1.  Check that all formalization files type-check:

        make build

    Expected result: successful completion (exit code 0).

2.  Check the theorem connecting typing rules and specification (Theorem 2):

        make -f RocqMakefile theories/Equiv.vo

    Expected result: successful completion (exit code 0).

3.  Check algorithm correctness proof (Theorem 3):

        make -f RocqMakefile theories/Algo.vo

    Expected result: successful completion (exit code 0).

4.  Check verified extraction of the algorithm:

        make -f RocqMakefile theories/Extr.vo
        ls extraction/type.ml

    Expected result: `extraction/type.ml` exists.

5.  Check proof documentation generation:

        make doc
        ls doc/index.html

    Expected result: `doc/index.html` exists.

If a step fails, re-run with:

    make clean
    make build

and include the failing command output in the review.

---

## ** FULL REVIEW **

This section provides a more complete checklist that validates all main claims.

## Setup

Use the Docker setup from the smoke test.

Run from the repository root:

    make clean
    make build

Expected runtime: usually under 10 minutes on a standard laptop.

1.  Reproduce the complete proof checking pipeline:

        make build

    This checks all files in `theories/`.

2.  Validate specification-to-type-system equivalence results:

        make -f RocqMakefile theories/Equiv.vo

    This covers the lemmas/theorem proving equivalence between the LRM-style specification and the bidirectional type system.

3.  Validate algorithm correctness:

        make -f RocqMakefile theories/Algo.vo

    This checks the theorem showing correctness of the executable typing algorithm with respect to the formal system.

4.  Validate executable extraction output:

        make -f RocqMakefile theories/Extr.vo
        wc -l extraction/type.ml

    The extracted OCaml file should be present and non-empty.

5.  Validate generated documentation artifacts:

        make doc
        ls doc/index.html

    Open `doc/index.html` in a browser to inspect the generated dependency-aware proof documentation.

## Expected reviewer outcome

All mandatory points 1-5 should finish without errors and with exit code 0.
No internet access is required.
